label.value: increased RNA level during cellular response to copper ion

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA measured in a cell during a cellular response to copper ions is higher than normal. Total RNA or a specific RNA may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: delayed onset of mitotic spindle assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which assembly of the mitotic spindle begins later than normal.

label.value: abolished protein localization to mitotic spindle pole body during metaphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the mitotic spindle pole body during metaphase does not occur.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic spindle microtubule depolymerization, i.e. the removal of tubulin dimers from a microtubule in the mitotic spindle, occurs to a lesser extent than normal.
A septation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell forms a secondary septum that is thinner than normal.

A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, and structure of the actomyosin contractile ring is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: delayed onset of actomyosin contractile ring contraction

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which actomyosin contractile ring contraction begins later than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell forms a secondary septum that is thinner than normal and does not extend over the entire cell division site.

label.value: increased protein localization to cell division site

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the site of cell division is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to telomere during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the telomere of a chromosome is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is inviable, and has one nucleus and more than one septum.
A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is inviable, and has two nuclei and more than one septum.

label.value: abolished protein phosphorylation during cellular response to UV

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, does not occur during a cellular response to ultraviolet light.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein phosphorylation during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, does not occur during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal viability following cellular response to UV

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after exposure to ultraviolet light.

label.value: normal viability following cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after exposure to methyl methanesulfonate.
A physical cellular phenotype in which linear elements are absent from the cell.

definition.value: In the absence of filamentous actin, a ring structure may form, but is not considered a contractile ring.

label.value: decreased meiotic sister chromatid cohesion along chromosome arms

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between sister chromatids is decreased along the length of the chromosome arms during meiosis.

label.value: normal meiotic sister chromatid cohesion at centromere

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between sister chromatids is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) at the centromeric regions during meiosis.
A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosome segregation begins earlier than normal.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to ferrozine. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of ferrozine that allows wild type cells to grow.

A cellular process phenotype in which macroautophagy is abnormal when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation. Macroautophagy is the major pathway by which cells digest parts of their own cytoplasm.

label.value: abolished protein localization to vacuole during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the vacuole is abolished when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: inviable elongated vegetative cell with fragmented nucleus

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetatively growing cell is inviable, is elongated, and contains a nucleus that is broken into small fragments.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002061) or one of its descendants.

label.value: inviable elongated multiseptate vegetative cell with fragmented nucleus

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetatively growing cell is inviable, is elongated, contains more than one septum, and contains a nucleus that is broken into small fragments.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002061) or one of its descendants.

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to dimethyl sulfoxide. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of dimethyl sulfoxide that allows wild type cells to grow.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing dimethyl sulfoxide.

label.value: abnormal purine-specific mismatch base pair DNA N-glycosylase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of purine-specific mismatch base pair DNA N-glycosylase activity is abnormal.

label.value: abolished purine-specific mismatch base pair DNA N-glycosylase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which purine-specific mismatch base pair DNA N-glycosylase activity is absent.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of mature, polyadenylated 25S rRNA measured in a cell is higher than normal.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of polyadenylated 25S rRNA measured in a cell is too low to detect.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of polyadenylated 5.8S rRNA measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of the mature polyadenylated 5.8S rRNA measured in a cell is lower than normal.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of polyadenylated 5S rRNA measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the nucleolus is partitioned to daughter cells unequally during cell division.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is inviable, is elongated, and has two nuclei but no septum.

definition.value: This phenotype may indicate that the cytokinesis after mitosis checkpoint is activated.

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to radicicol. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of radicicol that allows wild type cells to grow.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to streptothricin. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of streptothricin that allows wild type cells to grow.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to lovastatin. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of lovastatin that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: decreased cytosolic large ribosomal subunit level

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells contain fewer free large ribosomal subunits in the cytosol than normal.

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA transcribed from cenH measured in a cell is higher than normal. cenH is a region located between mat2-P and mat3-M that is homologous to centromeric repeats, and that produces non-coding RNAs and small interfering RNAs.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased histone H3-K9 acetylation at silent mating-type cassette during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which acetylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 at the silent mating-type cassettes occurs to a greater extent than normal.

A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is inviable, is shaped in the form of a sphere, and has a larger volume than normal. In a swollen cell, both length and diameter may be greater than normal, although the cell is only considered elongated if the length:diameter ratio is also greater than normal.

label.value: normal protein localization to mitotic spindle midzone

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the mitotic spindle midzone is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal viability following cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after exposure to hydroxyurea.
A cell phenotype in which DNA is broken into small fragments when the population in which the cell is found is in stationary phase.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0. Use 'fragmented DNA' (FYPO:0000160) or one of its descendants if DNA was detected using a method that can resolve molecule sizes (e.g. gel electrophoresis) or detect DNA ends (e.g. TUNEL assay). Otherwise, consider using 'fragmented nucleus' (FYPO:0001919) or one of its descendants.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more diglycerides measured in a cell is higher than normal.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to one or more fatty acids (usually supplied as the corresponding anions). Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of fatty acid that allows wild type cells to grow.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to 1,2-dioctanoyl-sn-glycerol (DiC8 DAG). Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of 1,2-dioctanoyl-sn-glycerol that allows wild type cells to grow.

A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of heme binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can mean that the mutated gene product itself binds heme less than wild type, or that a mutation in one gene decreases heme binding by a second gene product. When using this term, it is therefore recommended to note the specific protein(s) affected.
